    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Chemical Plant Safety</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Jack N Gerard of American Chemistry Council replies to June 14 editorial urging Congress to make chemical plants less vulnerable to terrorist attack; says Congress should not pass environmental bill masquerading as security bill</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Worse Than Nothing'' (editorial, June 14):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Worse Than Nothing'' (editorial, June 14):</p>
        <p>Congress should not pass an environmental bill masquerading as a security bill, which is what would happen if language is inserted mandating new chemical processes.</p>
        <p>Hundreds of thousands of Americans are employed in the chemistry sector. Their products are relied upon by industries and by the communities in which they live and work.</p>
        <p>Chemical security is a national issue that requires a uniform national response and not a patchwork of state-level solutions.</p>
        <p>Since 9/11, without any federal prompting, the 133 American Chemistry Council member companies have voluntarily invested nearly $3 billion in security.</p>
        <p>Security is good business, and we will continue to work with legislators of both parties to obtain a bill that achieves the nation's security goals.</p>
        <p>Jack N. Gerard  President and Chief Executive  American Chemistry Council  Arlington, Va., June 15, 2006</p>
      </block>
